snippet.textDisplay: Many years ago, I used to work as an operations analyst and we had a similar calendar scheme for productivity and financial reporting.  The calendar was divided into quarters and months one and two of each quarter had four weeks while month three had five;  Sunday to Saturday.  So, for example, January 2020 may have actually started back on Sunday, 29 December, and ended Saturday, 25 January (or, it may not have started until Sunday, 5-Jan!).  But, over time, the start of months would keep slipping backwards so that every few years we would add an extra week to December, making it a 6-week month, to "true up" the dates.

The if statement is wrong.
